## Tools Used

- Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS)
- Active Directory Users and Computers (ADUC)
- Group Policy Management Tool
- PowerShell (for delegation and password resets)
- Domain Controllers (authentication, SYSVOL distribution)

## Findings

- AD centralizes identity and policy management across large networks.
- OUs organize users/computers for policy application.
- Security groups manage permissions across resources.
- Delegation allows limited admin rights without full privileges.
- GPOs enforce security baselines (passwords, lock screens, restrictions).
- Kerberos is the secure default authentication; NetNTLM remains for legacy.
- Trees and forests scale AD across organizations; trusts enable cross-domain access.

## MMitigation / Best Practices

- Regularly review and update OUs and groups to match organizational structure.
- Apply GPOs to enforce strong password policies and session security.
- Use delegation to reduce reliance on Domain Admin accounts.
- Prefer Kerberos authentication; disable NetNTLM where possible.
- Implement forests and trusts carefully, granting only necessary cross-domain access.
- Harden Domain Controllers and monitor SYSVOL for integrity.

